1
00:00:39,144 --> 00:00:42,105
<i>I'm sure you're aware Japan's ratio</i>
<i>of determining the cause of death</i>

2
00:00:42,188 --> 00:00:43,815
is much lower than in other countries?

3
00:00:43,898 --> 00:00:44,732
Yes.

4
00:00:44,816 --> 00:00:46,150
To improve that,

5
00:00:46,234 --> 00:00:51,990
we're going to experimentally introduce
the American medical examiner system.

6
00:00:52,699 --> 00:00:54,367
Medical examiner?

7
00:00:54,450 --> 00:00:57,871
The biggest difference from Japan's system
is that medical examiners,

8
00:00:57,954 --> 00:01:01,624
<i>or forensic pathologists,</i>
<i>have investigative authority.</i>

9
00:01:16,973 --> 00:01:17,932
What?

10
00:01:18,474 --> 00:01:23,021
Does that mean doctors
can investigate cases like the police?

11
00:01:23,104 --> 00:01:25,732
No, not in exactly the same way,

12
00:01:25,815 --> 00:01:28,943
<i>but they can conduct investigations</i>
<i>to determine the cause of death.</i>

13
00:01:29,027 --> 00:01:31,779
<i>They also have the authority</i>
<i>to determine the need for an autopsy.</i>

14
00:01:33,907 --> 00:01:35,617
I see…

15
00:01:54,510 --> 00:01:55,428
<i>So,</i>

16
00:01:55,511 --> 00:01:57,931
<i>we're bringing in Dr. Masumi Mizusawa,</i>

17
00:01:58,014 --> 00:02:00,892
<i>who has worked as a medical examiner</i>
<i>in the US for 15 years.</i>

18
00:02:00,975 --> 00:02:02,268
And Ms. Kiryu,

19
00:02:02,352 --> 00:02:05,855
you'll be the director
of Medical Examiner Japan.

20
00:02:06,356 --> 00:02:07,357
Okay.

21
00:02:09,984 --> 00:02:10,902
What?

22
00:02:37,470 --> 00:02:39,347
Why am I being demoted?

23
00:02:39,430 --> 00:02:41,307
I mean, there's no way a policy change

24
00:02:41,391 --> 00:02:44,185
is going to increase the rate
of determining the cause of death.

25
00:02:45,061 --> 00:02:46,437
And you know,

26
00:02:46,521 --> 00:02:49,816
I became a bureaucrat
because I wanted to create systems

27
00:02:49,899 --> 00:02:52,860
that let everyone in this country
live their lives smiling.

28
00:02:53,444 --> 00:02:55,446
This topic is not even my specialty.

29
00:02:55,530 --> 00:02:57,073
I don't have the knowledge.

30
00:02:57,156 --> 00:02:59,283
And I'm supposed to be in charge on-site?

31
00:03:00,076 --> 00:03:01,661
There's no way I can do it.

32
00:03:06,374 --> 00:03:07,709
CENTER DIRECTOR
MAHO KIRYU

33
00:03:15,425 --> 00:03:17,093
Oh! Dr. Mizusawa?

34
00:03:17,176 --> 00:03:19,220
I'm Masumi Mizusawa.

35
00:03:19,303 --> 00:03:20,805
Call me Masumi.

36
00:03:20,888 --> 00:03:21,889
I'm Kiryu.

37
00:03:21,973 --> 00:03:23,975
-Pleasure to meet you.
-Same here.

38
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:25,560
Huh?

39
00:03:26,269 --> 00:03:28,354
-Did you just come from the airport?
-Yes.

40
00:03:29,355 --> 00:03:31,482
Are you okay with your jet lag?

41
00:03:31,566 --> 00:03:33,359
Well… I don't know.

42
00:03:33,443 --> 00:03:38,031
You know, jet lag is like rigor mortis.

43
00:03:38,823 --> 00:03:40,700
Jet lag is like rigor mortis?

44
00:03:41,367 --> 00:03:42,660
What do you mean?

45
00:03:42,744 --> 00:03:43,619
Well…

46
00:03:44,120 --> 00:03:47,206
Jet lag doesn't happen
just because of time.

47
00:03:47,290 --> 00:03:50,418
It depends on light exposure
and the amount of sleep.

48
00:03:50,918 --> 00:03:53,671
Rigor mortis isn't determined
by time alone either.

49
00:03:53,755 --> 00:03:57,050
It changes based on temperature,
humidity, and posture.

50
00:03:57,133 --> 00:04:01,179
In other words, both depend
not just on time, but on conditions.

51
00:04:04,182 --> 00:04:05,224
Oh, okay.

52
00:04:06,392 --> 00:04:07,352
Right…

53
00:04:07,435 --> 00:04:08,269
Good.

54
00:04:10,855 --> 00:04:14,734
It finally starts tomorrow,
the medical examiner system.

55
00:04:17,528 --> 00:04:19,781
Ms. Dojima, should we call them?

56
00:04:19,864 --> 00:04:20,823
Call who?

57
00:04:20,907 --> 00:04:23,117
You know, the new system starting today,

58
00:04:23,201 --> 00:04:26,079
where we have to report
all abnormal deaths

59
00:04:26,162 --> 00:04:28,831
to that, uh, medical examiner.

60
00:04:28,915 --> 00:04:31,459
Oh, that ridiculous system.

61
00:04:31,542 --> 00:04:33,294
No need to call them.

62
00:04:33,378 --> 00:04:34,212
Yes, ma'am!

63
00:04:34,295 --> 00:04:37,048
At this hour, no one would even
answer the phone, right?

64
00:04:37,131 --> 00:04:38,216
Call them then.

65
00:04:38,299 --> 00:04:40,468
It will prove
that we tried to contact them.

66
00:04:40,551 --> 00:04:42,261
Yes, ma'am! I will call them!

67
00:04:45,098 --> 00:04:45,973
They answered!

68
00:04:46,057 --> 00:04:47,683
Sorry to keep you waiting.

69
00:04:47,767 --> 00:04:48,768
It's fine.

70
00:04:48,851 --> 00:04:51,896
Decomposition doesn't progress much
at this hour.

71
00:04:53,272 --> 00:04:54,107
What?

72
00:04:55,024 --> 00:04:55,942
Hello.

73
00:05:22,927 --> 00:05:24,345
Who are you? What are you--

74
00:05:24,429 --> 00:05:25,513
Hey, stop!

75
00:05:25,596 --> 00:05:27,932
-He's the medical examiner.
-Huh?

76
00:05:28,015 --> 00:05:30,268
What's that? I wasn't told about it.

77
00:05:30,351 --> 00:05:31,811
I'm the supervisor, Kiryu.

78
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:34,730
With the new system, any unusual deaths

79
00:05:34,814 --> 00:05:37,358
must first be examined by
a forensic pathologist.

80
00:05:37,441 --> 00:05:38,985
The medical examiner will--

81
00:05:39,986 --> 00:05:40,903
Um…

82
00:05:44,615 --> 00:05:47,618
The deceased's mother
was the first to discover the body.

83
00:05:50,288 --> 00:05:52,331
His clothes are wet.

84
00:05:52,415 --> 00:05:54,417
Keitaro Aikawa, 17 years old.

85
00:05:54,500 --> 00:05:56,127
He didn't come home by dawn,

86
00:05:56,210 --> 00:05:59,672
so his mother got worried, searched
the neighborhood, and found him here.

87
00:05:59,755 --> 00:06:02,049
She called 119 and performed CPR.

88
00:06:02,133 --> 00:06:05,761
They determined he was clearly
already dead, so he wasn't transported.

89
00:06:05,845 --> 00:06:07,054
Found a smartphone.

90
00:06:07,138 --> 00:06:09,473
The pond is about 40 centimeters deep.

91
00:06:09,557 --> 00:06:10,766
-This is murder.
-Yes.

92
00:06:10,850 --> 00:06:13,769
There's no way someone drowns
in a pond this shallow.

93
00:06:14,812 --> 00:06:16,814
I'm sorry to bother you at a tough time.

94
00:06:16,898 --> 00:06:19,775
May I ask about the situation
when you found your son--

95
00:06:19,859 --> 00:06:21,777
Hey, don't… I'm sorry, Ma'am.

96
00:06:21,861 --> 00:06:22,945
Back off.

97
00:06:23,654 --> 00:06:24,739
Doctor.

98
00:06:24,822 --> 00:06:27,575
Could you stop interfering
in the investigation?

99
00:06:29,202 --> 00:06:30,494
I'm not interfering.

100
00:06:30,578 --> 00:06:31,412
What?

101
00:06:31,495 --> 00:06:32,955
You just did.

102
00:06:33,039 --> 00:06:36,042
This is a legitimate investigation
based on the authority

103
00:06:36,125 --> 00:06:38,419
granted to a medical examiner.

104
00:06:39,879 --> 00:06:41,214
Supervisor.

105
00:06:41,923 --> 00:06:43,758
Care to explain what's going on?

106
00:06:46,469 --> 00:06:49,180
In order to determine the cause of death,

107
00:06:49,263 --> 00:06:51,766
medical examiners
are granted investigative rights.

108
00:06:51,849 --> 00:06:53,434
Are you playing detective?

109
00:06:53,517 --> 00:06:56,687
Also, under this system,
all abnormal deaths must be evaluated,

110
00:06:56,771 --> 00:06:59,357
and the medical examiner
decides if an autopsy is needed.

111
00:06:59,440 --> 00:07:01,108
It's clearly a murder.

112
00:07:01,192 --> 00:07:02,860
It is, it is a murder!

113
00:07:02,944 --> 00:07:06,322
We still don't know
whether it's a homicide.

114
00:07:10,451 --> 00:07:11,410
You're in my way.

115
00:07:38,020 --> 00:07:40,481
Why is a bureaucrat the director here?

116
00:07:41,732 --> 00:07:42,567
What?

117
00:07:43,067 --> 00:07:45,069
Do you even have a medical license?

118
00:07:45,152 --> 00:07:46,445
Do you?

119
00:07:48,322 --> 00:07:52,994
No, I don't, but this is not only
a medical institution, it's also part of

120
00:07:53,077 --> 00:07:56,289
the country's policy
in determining the cause of death.

121
00:07:56,372 --> 00:07:59,458
There's a document from the Ministry
about autopsy regulations, right?

122
00:07:59,542 --> 00:08:00,459
Yes.

123
00:08:00,543 --> 00:08:03,254
Created by the department
overseeing the medical system.

124
00:08:03,838 --> 00:08:07,049
That document
is completely useless in the field.

125
00:08:07,550 --> 00:08:09,885
You don't say.

126
00:08:10,386 --> 00:08:11,679
Really?

127
00:08:13,014 --> 00:08:14,223
Of course, it is.

128
00:08:14,307 --> 00:08:17,268
It was made by bureaucrats
who don't understand the field.

129
00:08:27,236 --> 00:08:28,404
Let's begin.

130
00:09:00,353 --> 00:09:01,896
Are you okay?

131
00:09:01,979 --> 00:09:03,272
I'm totally fine.

132
00:09:04,815 --> 00:09:07,360
The cause of death is drowning.

133
00:09:07,443 --> 00:09:09,945
In a 40-centimeter-deep pond?

134
00:09:10,029 --> 00:09:12,406
-Yes.
-How could he have drowned there?

135
00:09:12,490 --> 00:09:15,368
So he drowned somewhere else
and was moved there?

136
00:09:15,451 --> 00:09:16,952
No, that doesn't add up.

137
00:09:17,036 --> 00:09:19,955
The plankton in the pond water
matches what was in his lungs.

138
00:09:20,039 --> 00:09:23,000
That means he was alive
when he entered the water.

139
00:09:23,084 --> 00:09:27,254
So he was assaulted, lost consciousness,
and then thrown into the pond?

140
00:09:27,338 --> 00:09:29,757
There were small abrasions on his palms.

141
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:32,343
Possibly defensive injuries
from when he fell.

142
00:09:32,426 --> 00:09:35,596
That suggests he was conscious,
trying to defend himself.

143
00:09:35,680 --> 00:09:36,764
It doesn't add up.

144
00:09:36,847 --> 00:09:41,143
So then, he was pushed
into the pond while conscious?

145
00:09:41,227 --> 00:09:44,897
The pond is 40 centimeters deep.
He should have been able to stand up.

146
00:09:44,980 --> 00:09:46,023
It doesn't add up.

147
00:09:46,107 --> 00:09:49,276
Then maybe someone held his face down
while he tried to get up.

148
00:09:49,360 --> 00:09:53,656
That would leave marks on the head,
neck, and shoulders.

149
00:09:53,739 --> 00:09:55,116
It doesn't add up.

150
00:09:55,199 --> 00:09:58,536
So then how did he drown
in a 40-centimeter-deep pond?

151
00:09:58,619 --> 00:09:59,662
Who knows?

152
00:10:00,162 --> 00:10:01,706
I wonder.

153
00:10:02,456 --> 00:10:03,666
It's a mystery.

154
00:10:08,170 --> 00:10:09,171
Well, whatever.

155
00:10:10,131 --> 00:10:10,965
Then,

156
00:10:11,632 --> 00:10:13,718
what about signs of assault?

157
00:10:21,934 --> 00:10:27,356
There are injuries to the head and chest
caused by external force.

158
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:30,693
First, on the head, the marks
are concentrated in two places.

159
00:10:30,776 --> 00:10:34,905
Likely left by a great external force,
such as from a weapon.

160
00:10:34,989 --> 00:10:37,950
As for the chest fractures,
there are three patterns.

161
00:10:38,033 --> 00:10:40,870
One was caused by CPR.

162
00:10:40,953 --> 00:10:44,373
There was no bleeding or vital reaction.

163
00:10:44,874 --> 00:10:46,667
In regard to this area,

164
00:10:46,751 --> 00:10:52,006
it shows a significant loss of blood,
and was very likely caused by assault.

165
00:10:52,089 --> 00:10:53,799
And the last one

166
00:10:53,883 --> 00:10:56,719
is one that can't be explained
by either of the other two.

167
00:10:58,387 --> 00:11:03,058
It does not show a strong vital reaction,
but there was something.

168
00:11:03,142 --> 00:11:06,979
This mark shows the slightest
amount of vital reaction.

169
00:11:07,062 --> 00:11:09,273
Is that the clue to
determining it was homicide?

170
00:11:09,356 --> 00:11:11,358
I don't know if it will or not.

171
00:11:11,442 --> 00:11:16,030
But it might be a piece of the puzzle
to solve the mystery.

172
00:11:19,033 --> 00:11:22,036
Anyway, solve it quickly.

173
00:11:22,119 --> 00:11:23,787
-Supervisor.
-Yes?

174
00:11:24,371 --> 00:11:26,582
Do your job and supervise.

175
00:11:36,217 --> 00:11:37,343
What's that?

176
00:11:38,135 --> 00:11:40,846
The content of the notebook by the pond.

177
00:11:40,930 --> 00:11:42,431
<i>The phone next to it</i>

178
00:11:42,515 --> 00:11:45,142
was the one that belonged to
Keitaro Aikawa.

179
00:11:45,226 --> 00:11:47,394
Then the phone in the pond…

180
00:11:47,478 --> 00:11:48,979
Still being verified.

181
00:11:51,565 --> 00:11:54,026
Does anyone know what this means?

182
00:11:54,527 --> 00:11:56,779
For now, it's a mystery.

183
00:11:56,862 --> 00:12:00,366
We identified the owner of the phone.

184
00:12:00,449 --> 00:12:02,826
-What?
-Ryoya Sakagami, 17 years old.

185
00:12:02,910 --> 00:12:04,286
One arrest for marijuana dealing.

186
00:12:04,370 --> 00:12:05,955
He's a member of a group

187
00:12:06,038 --> 00:12:09,041
<i>based out of Club Heads</i>
<i>that engages in fraud and drug dealing.</i>

188
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:18,217
Why are you running away?

189
00:12:20,719 --> 00:12:21,595
Hey!

190
00:12:24,473 --> 00:12:27,142
Police! Nobody move!

191
00:12:34,817 --> 00:12:38,529
When was the last time
you saw Ryoya Sakagami?

192
00:12:39,321 --> 00:12:41,782
You were having him sell marijuana,
were you not?

193
00:12:41,865 --> 00:12:43,450
Don't know him.

194
00:12:43,534 --> 00:12:46,870
Cut the crap! Don't cover for a murderer!

195
00:12:47,371 --> 00:12:48,581
Murderer?

196
00:12:49,623 --> 00:12:50,499
Ryoya?

197
00:12:51,875 --> 00:12:53,043
Who did he kill?

198
00:12:53,127 --> 00:12:55,879
-Aikawa--
-A 17-year-old boy.

199
00:13:00,509 --> 00:13:01,552
You don't mean…

200
00:13:02,720 --> 00:13:03,929
Keitaro?

201
00:13:08,017 --> 00:13:09,935
How do you know that?

202
00:13:10,686 --> 00:13:12,730
Was he one of your group too?

203
00:13:14,023 --> 00:13:15,441
Any marijuana show up?

204
00:13:15,524 --> 00:13:16,775
Initially not,

205
00:13:16,859 --> 00:13:19,528
but when we retested
using liquid chromatography,

206
00:13:19,612 --> 00:13:23,365
marijuana was detected
in Keitaro Aikawa's blood and urine.

207
00:13:23,449 --> 00:13:24,491
I knew it.

208
00:13:24,575 --> 00:13:26,243
Huh? What does that mean?

209
00:13:26,327 --> 00:13:29,079
<i>Keitaro Aikawa</i>
<i>was part of a marijuana trafficking group.</i>

210
00:13:29,163 --> 00:13:32,708
<i>He and one of the members, Ryoya Sakagami,</i>
<i>ran off with the marijuana.</i>

211
00:13:32,791 --> 00:13:35,711
Then, they may have had
a falling out, and he was killed.

212
00:13:35,794 --> 00:13:39,757
<i>We're currently tracking Ryoya Sakagami</i>
<i>as a key person of interest.</i>

213
00:13:39,840 --> 00:13:42,468
I'm going to Keitaro Aikawa's home.

214
00:13:42,551 --> 00:13:44,970
-What's that?
-Some questions need answers.

215
00:13:45,054 --> 00:13:47,014
The numbers and arrows in the notebook,

216
00:13:47,097 --> 00:13:49,350
the weak vital signs
of the chest fracture,

217
00:13:49,433 --> 00:13:52,102
and why he drowned
in a 40-centimeter-deep pond.

218
00:13:52,186 --> 00:13:54,521
There may be pieces there
that solve these mysteries.

219
00:13:54,605 --> 00:13:55,939
Hey, Supervisor!

220
00:13:56,023 --> 00:13:59,360
Medical examiners are granted
investigative rights to gather info--

221
00:13:59,443 --> 00:14:01,070
-Hold on!
-Wait!

222
00:14:07,785 --> 00:14:09,036
SONGWRITING NOTES VOL 3

223
00:14:10,913 --> 00:14:12,331
SONGWRITING NOTES VOL 3

224
00:14:24,468 --> 00:14:26,178
DID THE SOUND GET WORSE??

225
00:14:30,140 --> 00:14:31,266
IT'S NOT FAIR

226
00:14:31,350 --> 00:14:32,476
GOD SAVE ME

227
00:14:33,978 --> 00:14:34,812
WHY?

228
00:14:34,895 --> 00:14:36,230
I'M SCARED… REALLY SCARED

229
00:14:39,233 --> 00:14:40,317
IT'S OVER

230
00:14:40,401 --> 00:14:41,860
I'M SO, SO SCARED

231
00:14:41,944 --> 00:14:43,237
SHIT SHIT SHIT

232
00:14:50,744 --> 00:14:51,787
Ms. Dojima.

233
00:14:51,870 --> 00:14:53,497
No marijuana was found.

234
00:14:56,291 --> 00:14:57,167
Let's go.

235
00:14:57,251 --> 00:14:58,127
Okay.

236
00:15:05,884 --> 00:15:09,138
Did Keitaro like music?

237
00:15:09,888 --> 00:15:12,016
If you're done, leave already.

238
00:15:25,571 --> 00:15:27,281
Man, I'm exhausted.

239
00:15:27,364 --> 00:15:29,908
Today felt insanely long. Way too long.

240
00:15:30,701 --> 00:15:32,911
Being demoted was humiliating enough,

241
00:15:32,995 --> 00:15:35,706
but going out into the field
made it even worse.

242
00:15:35,789 --> 00:15:37,499
I really can't do anything.

243
00:15:39,793 --> 00:15:42,588
I'm just there. Just watching.
But I'm the one in charge.

244
00:15:42,671 --> 00:15:44,590
I want to go back to my old job.

245
00:15:45,257 --> 00:15:47,885
There's no way
I'm stuck in the field forever, right?

246
00:15:49,136 --> 00:15:51,221
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

247
00:16:09,573 --> 00:16:12,701
He really liked music.

248
00:16:14,620 --> 00:16:16,038
It sounds silly, but…

249
00:16:17,456 --> 00:16:20,334
he used to say he wanted to be a musician…

250
00:16:22,336 --> 00:16:23,295
Even though

251
00:16:24,797 --> 00:16:27,841
becoming one
is harder than winning the lottery.

252
00:16:29,593 --> 00:16:30,511
But

253
00:16:31,553 --> 00:16:32,554
then…

254
00:16:34,723 --> 00:16:36,475
his hearing went bad.

255
00:16:39,311 --> 00:16:40,437
He said

256
00:16:41,814 --> 00:16:43,649
he was giving up on music.

257
00:16:45,442 --> 00:16:47,611
He had worked so hard at it,

258
00:16:48,278 --> 00:16:49,238
<i>so I think</i>

259
00:16:50,114 --> 00:16:51,782
<i>it was a massive shock to him.</i>

260
00:16:57,121 --> 00:16:58,247
Around that time,

261
00:17:00,082 --> 00:17:01,041
Ryoya…

262
00:17:03,043 --> 00:17:06,171
a delinquent he knew
from middle school, invited him.

263
00:17:07,214 --> 00:17:08,590
Because of him…

264
00:17:10,634 --> 00:17:12,261
Keitaro joined a bad crowd.

265
00:17:18,892 --> 00:17:20,102
Marijuana, huh?

266
00:17:21,186 --> 00:17:22,354
Maybe he…

267
00:17:26,108 --> 00:17:28,569
Maybe he was a good-for-nothing kid,

268
00:17:29,236 --> 00:17:30,612
but to me,

269
00:17:32,322 --> 00:17:34,074
he was my precious child.

270
00:17:38,620 --> 00:17:42,082
I want to know why this happened.

271
00:17:45,169 --> 00:17:47,087
I want to know what happened.

272
00:17:48,046 --> 00:17:50,215
The whole truth.

273
00:17:53,844 --> 00:17:54,970
Please.

274
00:17:56,763 --> 00:17:58,932
Find out the truth.

275
00:18:01,643 --> 00:18:03,270
If he was murdered…

276
00:18:06,023 --> 00:18:07,566
I will never forgive them.

277
00:18:10,569 --> 00:18:13,405
I have no future left, anyway.

278
00:18:14,656 --> 00:18:17,284
I'll live my life just to hate the killer.

279
00:18:46,230 --> 00:18:47,522
What are you doing?

280
00:18:52,611 --> 00:18:54,279
What? Sudoku?

281
00:19:35,028 --> 00:19:36,488
Hey, where are you going?

282
00:19:36,571 --> 00:19:38,407
-The pond.
-What?

283
00:19:38,490 --> 00:19:40,993
There might be a piece
I haven't found yet.

284
00:19:46,456 --> 00:19:47,708
What are you doing here?

285
00:19:48,166 --> 00:19:49,126
Investigating.

286
00:19:49,710 --> 00:19:51,336
Investigating, huh?

287
00:19:52,337 --> 00:19:54,214
Did the police find out anything?

288
00:19:58,885 --> 00:20:00,637
It wasn't on the day of the crime.

289
00:20:00,721 --> 00:20:03,223
He was seen with a man
thought to be Ryoya Sakagami.

290
00:20:03,307 --> 00:20:05,684
Standing opposite each other
across the pond.

291
00:20:05,767 --> 00:20:10,022
They were shouting, clapping,
and throwing stones into the water.

292
00:20:10,814 --> 00:20:13,650
Most likely, they were just high
and acting out.

293
00:20:26,413 --> 00:20:28,582
Oh, it's Ms. Dojima. Excuse me.

294
00:20:28,665 --> 00:20:29,791
Don't answer.

295
00:20:29,875 --> 00:20:31,752
-No, but--
-I said don't answer it.

296
00:20:35,255 --> 00:20:36,298
What?

297
00:21:19,883 --> 00:21:21,051
The pieces

298
00:21:21,885 --> 00:21:22,886
might be…

299
00:21:25,138 --> 00:21:26,431
coming together.

300
00:21:40,987 --> 00:21:41,863
Hey!

301
00:21:43,657 --> 00:21:44,699
Damn it!

302
00:21:46,410 --> 00:21:47,702
Let me go!

303
00:21:49,996 --> 00:21:51,164
Now what?

304
00:21:51,248 --> 00:21:53,834
<i>-I would like you to check something.</i>
-What?

305
00:21:53,917 --> 00:21:57,295
About the apps on Keitaro Aikawa's phone.

306
00:21:57,379 --> 00:21:58,505
Look, forget it.

307
00:21:58,588 --> 00:22:01,675
They caught Ryoya Sakagami,
and the interrogation is about to start.

308
00:22:01,758 --> 00:22:03,343
I'll be right there!

309
00:22:05,262 --> 00:22:07,639
-You're even coming to the interrogation?
<i>-Yes.</i>

310
00:22:07,722 --> 00:22:11,893
Based on the legitimate authority
granted to a medical examiner--

311
00:22:11,977 --> 00:22:13,437
Enough!

312
00:22:13,520 --> 00:22:14,980
Fine, I get it.

313
00:22:16,148 --> 00:22:19,651
You went to the pond on April 6th, right?

314
00:22:22,320 --> 00:22:24,156
What happened there?

315
00:22:29,327 --> 00:22:30,829
What did you do?

316
00:22:35,917 --> 00:22:37,419
I didn't go to the pond.

317
00:22:37,502 --> 00:22:40,547
Then why was your phone found in the pond?

318
00:22:48,096 --> 00:22:49,139
Excuse me.

319
00:22:49,222 --> 00:22:51,933
May I ask a question?

320
00:22:59,357 --> 00:23:00,483
Go ahead.

321
00:23:12,621 --> 00:23:14,206
Do you know

322
00:23:14,998 --> 00:23:16,041
what this is?

323
00:23:22,839 --> 00:23:24,090
You know

324
00:23:25,342 --> 00:23:27,093
what this means, don't you?

325
00:23:35,018 --> 00:23:35,852
Yes.

326
00:23:43,985 --> 00:23:45,028
And,

327
00:23:46,404 --> 00:23:51,243
there were three types of fractures
on Keitaro Aikawa's chest.

328
00:23:52,869 --> 00:23:53,912
The first

329
00:23:54,621 --> 00:23:56,081
was from being assaulted.

330
00:23:57,457 --> 00:23:58,625
The second

331
00:23:59,167 --> 00:24:02,212
was from his mother performing CPR.

332
00:24:05,298 --> 00:24:06,508
The third one…

333
00:24:08,510 --> 00:24:09,844
was from you, right?

334
00:24:20,939 --> 00:24:22,315
What happened?

335
00:24:30,407 --> 00:24:31,783
I'm sorry.

336
00:24:35,328 --> 00:24:36,371
I'm sorry.

337
00:24:37,998 --> 00:24:39,332
I'm sorry.

338
00:24:43,253 --> 00:24:44,671
I'm sorry.

339
00:24:49,759 --> 00:24:51,136
I'm sorry.

340
00:24:52,220 --> 00:24:53,555
I'm sorry.

341
00:25:01,771 --> 00:25:06,026
I will now explain
the cause of Keitaro's death.

342
00:25:07,068 --> 00:25:08,236
Please.

343
00:25:09,529 --> 00:25:10,905
We determined

344
00:25:10,989 --> 00:25:13,491
that the cause of death was drowning.

345
00:25:15,076 --> 00:25:18,455
First, around 5:00 p.m. the prior evening,

346
00:25:18,538 --> 00:25:21,082
<i>he was struck in the head,</i>
<i>causing a hematoma,</i>

347
00:25:21,166 --> 00:25:22,876
<i>essentially a lump.</i>

348
00:25:23,376 --> 00:25:27,547
Left alone, it was an injury
that would have healed naturally.

349
00:25:29,716 --> 00:25:32,927
After that, Keitaro came to this pond.

350
00:25:34,387 --> 00:25:36,514
This pond has a bridge spanning it,

351
00:25:36,598 --> 00:25:38,808
and the surrounding slopes
form a bowl shape,

352
00:25:38,892 --> 00:25:41,811
creating an environment
where sound echoes easily.

353
00:25:46,900 --> 00:25:48,568
MASUMI MIZUSAWA

354
00:25:51,863 --> 00:25:54,532
The sound bounces back
from various directions,

355
00:25:54,616 --> 00:25:58,078
making you lose sense
of where it's actually coming from.

356
00:25:58,661 --> 00:26:01,414
For Keitaro, who was hard of hearing
in his left ear,

357
00:26:01,498 --> 00:26:03,583
it was particularly confusing.

358
00:26:21,810 --> 00:26:23,853
Then, at around 10:00 p.m. that night,

359
00:26:23,937 --> 00:26:26,398
<i>while Keitaro was standing</i>
<i>at the edge of the pond,</i>

360
00:26:26,481 --> 00:26:28,525
<i>a motorcycle horn honked.</i>

361
00:26:29,901 --> 00:26:34,239
A horn is designed to resonate loudly
in a specific direction ahead.

362
00:26:34,781 --> 00:26:37,575
<i>Keitaro got startled by it,</i>

363
00:26:37,659 --> 00:26:40,537
<i>feeling as though the sound source</i>
<i>was close to him.</i>

364
00:26:40,620 --> 00:26:44,541
<i>He instinctively tried to avoid</i>
<i>the loud noise from an unknown direction,</i>

365
00:26:44,624 --> 00:26:47,001
<i>and it is likely that he slipped.</i>

366
00:26:47,085 --> 00:26:48,253
<i>He fell into the pond</i>

367
00:26:48,336 --> 00:26:50,880
<i>and hit his head on the water's surface.</i>

368
00:26:51,589 --> 00:26:52,757
<i>At that moment,</i>

369
00:26:52,841 --> 00:26:56,302
<i>a second impact was delivered</i>
<i>to a brain that had already been damaged.</i>

370
00:26:56,386 --> 00:27:00,682
This is known as Second Impact Syndrome.

371
00:27:01,683 --> 00:27:05,812
If the brain receives a second blow
before it has recovered from the first,

372
00:27:06,438 --> 00:27:11,776
even a minor force can amplify the damage
and lead to a fatal outcome.

373
00:27:12,360 --> 00:27:13,653
<i>In Keitaro's case,</i>

374
00:27:13,736 --> 00:27:17,323
<i>he suffered a severe concussion</i>
<i>and lost consciousness.</i>

375
00:27:17,949 --> 00:27:19,159
As a result,

376
00:27:20,034 --> 00:27:24,205
he drowned in a pond
only 40 centimeters deep.

377
00:27:26,166 --> 00:27:27,000
What?

378
00:27:28,918 --> 00:27:29,794
In other words,

379
00:27:31,421 --> 00:27:34,883
it was a tragic accident resulting
from a series of coincidences.

380
00:27:38,136 --> 00:27:39,220
An accident?

381
00:27:46,769 --> 00:27:49,314
If he hadn't been hit in the head,

382
00:27:49,397 --> 00:27:51,024
he wouldn't have died, right?

383
00:27:52,984 --> 00:27:55,361
If that horn hadn't been honked,

384
00:27:55,445 --> 00:27:56,988
he wouldn't have died.

385
00:27:58,114 --> 00:28:01,451
He died because someone did those things,
didn't he?

386
00:28:03,995 --> 00:28:06,748
And yet, you call it an accident.

387
00:28:10,043 --> 00:28:11,628
I won't accept that.

388
00:28:12,587 --> 00:28:14,130
I can't let it be.

389
00:28:15,632 --> 00:28:17,592
Keitaro was murdered.

390
00:28:19,511 --> 00:28:21,471
Wasn't it Ryoya who honked the horn?

391
00:28:21,554 --> 00:28:23,973
I know he rides a bike.

392
00:28:24,057 --> 00:28:26,309
That boy killed Keitaro, right?

393
00:28:26,392 --> 00:28:28,811
Arrest him. Aren't you the police?

394
00:28:28,895 --> 00:28:31,105
I understand how you feel.

395
00:28:31,189 --> 00:28:33,274
But based on the objective facts,

396
00:28:33,358 --> 00:28:36,653
the police are treating this case
as an accident.

397
00:28:36,736 --> 00:28:41,032
We have released the person of interest
after questioning.

398
00:28:41,115 --> 00:28:42,909
That's not right.

399
00:28:43,535 --> 00:28:45,495
Keitaro is dead,

400
00:28:45,578 --> 00:28:47,914
so why does he get to live a normal life?

401
00:28:50,416 --> 00:28:51,918
I understand how you feel,

402
00:28:52,418 --> 00:28:56,923
but these are the facts
derived from a forensic perspective.

403
00:28:58,132 --> 00:28:59,175
I told you

404
00:29:00,593 --> 00:29:02,971
I can't accept that.

405
00:29:11,437 --> 00:29:13,481
Shouldn't we tell her about it?

406
00:29:15,692 --> 00:29:16,776
That thing?

407
00:29:24,784 --> 00:29:25,994
Yes.

408
00:29:36,087 --> 00:29:40,091
My job is to convey the results
of the cause-of-death investigation.

409
00:29:41,426 --> 00:29:44,637
Anything else is not for me to say.

410
00:29:46,806 --> 00:29:47,765
However…

411
00:29:50,018 --> 00:29:52,270
you are the supervisor, Ms. Kiryu.

412
00:29:54,606 --> 00:29:57,191
If there is something else
you want to convey,

413
00:29:57,275 --> 00:30:00,153
please use your own judgment.

414
00:30:15,084 --> 00:30:16,502
<i>But to me,</i>

415
00:30:16,586 --> 00:30:18,838
he was my precious child.

416
00:30:18,922 --> 00:30:20,965
I want to know what happened.

417
00:30:21,549 --> 00:30:23,468
The whole truth.

418
00:30:34,896 --> 00:30:38,232
The one who honked the horn
was Ryoya Sakagami.

419
00:30:38,816 --> 00:30:39,609
Hey.

420
00:30:40,860 --> 00:30:42,236
What are you doing?

421
00:30:42,862 --> 00:30:44,989
It's the decision of the supervisor.

422
00:30:47,617 --> 00:30:49,035
Do what you want.

423
00:30:49,118 --> 00:30:51,371
The police won't take responsibility.

424
00:31:00,213 --> 00:31:01,381
Ms. Aikawa…

425
00:31:02,882 --> 00:31:07,011
Keitaro hadn't given up on his dream.

426
00:31:08,346 --> 00:31:10,014
How could you know that?

427
00:31:11,182 --> 00:31:14,936
It's the arrows and numbers
written in the notebook.

428
00:31:17,105 --> 00:31:19,649
<i>Because Keitaro</i>
<i>could only hear out of one ear,</i>

429
00:31:19,732 --> 00:31:24,070
<i>the direction sound was coming from</i>
<i>differed from the actual source.</i>

430
00:31:27,740 --> 00:31:30,243
<i>He was using this pond</i>
<i>to confirm that deviation,</i>

431
00:31:30,326 --> 00:31:32,787
<i>and was trying to correct it himself.</i>

432
00:31:35,331 --> 00:31:37,458
Close! You're almost there.

433
00:31:41,629 --> 00:31:43,589
<i>The arrows are the direction of the sound,</i>

434
00:31:43,673 --> 00:31:46,009
<i>and the numbers represent</i>
<i>the angle of the shift.</i>

435
00:31:48,052 --> 00:31:49,721
You're amazing, Keitaro.

436
00:31:49,804 --> 00:31:51,723
You're making progress.

437
00:31:52,682 --> 00:31:54,767
I shouldn't have invited you
into the gang.

438
00:31:55,727 --> 00:31:56,853
I'm really sorry.

439
00:32:00,398 --> 00:32:03,234
Do you think I can still be a musician?

440
00:32:05,653 --> 00:32:06,821
You will.

441
00:32:07,739 --> 00:32:08,990
If anyone can, it's you.

442
00:32:10,199 --> 00:32:11,951
So you have to get out of the gang.

443
00:32:15,079 --> 00:32:15,997
Right.

444
00:32:17,790 --> 00:32:18,708
But,

445
00:32:19,542 --> 00:32:21,753
my mom used to say all the time

446
00:32:21,836 --> 00:32:26,799
that becoming a musician
is harder than winning the lottery.

447
00:32:31,054 --> 00:32:34,599
And then, on that day, Keitaro was…

448
00:32:39,145 --> 00:32:39,979
I…

449
00:32:41,898 --> 00:32:43,316
want out.

450
00:32:44,067 --> 00:32:45,026
I don't want…

451
00:32:47,236 --> 00:32:48,780
to sell marijuana anymore.

452
00:32:59,207 --> 00:33:00,374
Come here!

453
00:33:01,501 --> 00:33:04,754
<i>The trace amount of marijuana</i>
<i>detected in Keitaro</i>

454
00:33:04,837 --> 00:33:07,507
<i>was most likely from secondhand smoke.</i>

455
00:33:21,062 --> 00:33:23,064
Can't you just let Keitaro go?

456
00:33:24,857 --> 00:33:26,609
I'll sell his share too.

457
00:33:27,902 --> 00:33:28,986
Just please

458
00:33:30,029 --> 00:33:31,322
let Keitaro out.

459
00:33:42,583 --> 00:33:43,543
Please!

460
00:33:44,502 --> 00:33:45,336
Hey.

461
00:33:46,087 --> 00:33:47,088
Hey!

462
00:33:47,171 --> 00:33:48,714
Stand up, asshole.

463
00:33:49,298 --> 00:33:50,716
Don't fuck with us!

464
00:33:52,969 --> 00:33:54,262
Please…

465
00:33:55,263 --> 00:33:56,139
Please!

466
00:33:56,222 --> 00:33:57,890
-You little shit…
-Please…

467
00:33:57,974 --> 00:33:58,850
Take that!

468
00:34:03,563 --> 00:34:04,480
Bastard!

469
00:34:04,564 --> 00:34:05,481
Please.

470
00:34:10,987 --> 00:34:12,238
Please.

471
00:34:12,321 --> 00:34:13,990
You little shit…

472
00:34:18,578 --> 00:34:19,662
Please.

473
00:34:23,374 --> 00:34:24,333
In exchange,

474
00:34:24,417 --> 00:34:27,128
you bring in three million yen
in one week.

475
00:34:38,347 --> 00:34:39,765
Thank you!

476
00:34:43,227 --> 00:34:44,645
Thank you!

477
00:34:49,108 --> 00:34:50,735
Thank you!

478
00:35:10,296 --> 00:35:11,547
Lame.

479
00:35:16,177 --> 00:35:17,553
He honked his horn

480
00:35:19,180 --> 00:35:21,807
because he wanted to tell Keitaro
the good news.

481
00:35:25,144 --> 00:35:28,231
He was just happy and honked it.

482
00:35:36,864 --> 00:35:37,823
Hey!

483
00:35:38,616 --> 00:35:40,409
Quit messing around.

484
00:35:48,751 --> 00:35:50,044
Keitaro!

485
00:35:50,127 --> 00:35:52,129
Hey! Keitaro? Hey!

486
00:35:52,213 --> 00:35:53,172
Hey!

487
00:35:56,592 --> 00:35:57,718
Keitaro!

488
00:35:57,802 --> 00:35:59,720
Keitaro!

489
00:35:59,804 --> 00:36:01,222
Keitaro!

490
00:36:02,265 --> 00:36:03,391
Keitaro…

491
00:36:04,267 --> 00:36:06,477
Keitaro!

492
00:36:06,560 --> 00:36:07,770
Keitaro…

493
00:36:19,699 --> 00:36:21,534
<i>I thought he might have died</i>

494
00:36:23,077 --> 00:36:25,037
<i>because of the CPR I gave him.</i>

495
00:36:28,582 --> 00:36:30,001
I got scared and ran away.

496
00:36:35,881 --> 00:36:37,008
I'm sorry.

497
00:36:48,227 --> 00:36:50,187
If Ryoya had called an ambulance,

498
00:36:51,439 --> 00:36:52,857
would he have lived?

499
00:36:55,109 --> 00:36:56,027
No.

500
00:36:58,154 --> 00:36:59,697
Even if he had called one,

501
00:37:00,698 --> 00:37:02,825
the result would have been the same.

502
00:37:05,578 --> 00:37:08,706
There was a fracture
on Keitaro's chest that showed

503
00:37:08,789 --> 00:37:11,500
a very slight vital reaction.

504
00:37:12,626 --> 00:37:13,586
That was

505
00:37:14,754 --> 00:37:17,131
from the CPR performed

506
00:37:18,132 --> 00:37:20,092
by Ryoya Sakagami.

507
00:37:21,969 --> 00:37:25,222
The fact that the vital reaction
was so minimal

508
00:37:25,306 --> 00:37:28,809
proves that the CPR
was performed immediately after death.

509
00:37:28,893 --> 00:37:31,729
In other words, it means that Keitaro

510
00:37:33,439 --> 00:37:35,399
had already passed away.

511
00:37:48,537 --> 00:37:49,580
Ms. Aikawa.

512
00:37:52,500 --> 00:37:54,043
CPR…

513
00:37:56,295 --> 00:37:57,755
was performed twice.

514
00:38:00,800 --> 00:38:06,305
The two sets of marks
on Keitaro's chest were both

515
00:38:07,390 --> 00:38:08,682
left by people

516
00:38:10,101 --> 00:38:13,896
who desperately wanted him to live.

517
00:38:18,943 --> 00:38:20,236
Keitaro…

518
00:38:20,903 --> 00:38:22,238
Keitaro!

519
00:38:22,738 --> 00:38:23,948
Please!

520
00:38:24,698 --> 00:38:25,699
Keitaro!

521
00:38:26,367 --> 00:38:27,660
Stay with me, Keitaro!

522
00:38:27,743 --> 00:38:28,994
Keitaro!

523
00:38:29,787 --> 00:38:30,704
Keitaro!

524
00:38:30,788 --> 00:38:32,164
Keitaro!

525
00:38:32,248 --> 00:38:33,916
Please!

526
00:38:33,999 --> 00:38:35,459
Keitaro!

527
00:38:35,543 --> 00:38:36,627
Keitaro!

528
00:38:36,710 --> 00:38:37,795
Keitaro!

529
00:38:37,878 --> 00:38:39,296
Keitaro!

530
00:38:40,172 --> 00:38:41,674
Keitaro!

531
00:38:41,757 --> 00:38:43,050
Keitaro!

532
00:38:50,057 --> 00:38:51,142
So…

533
00:38:56,230 --> 00:38:58,274
you're telling me to forgive him?

534
00:39:05,156 --> 00:39:06,949
Don't make it sound so simple.

535
00:40:28,906 --> 00:40:30,950
Dying like that…

536
00:40:33,035 --> 00:40:35,913
is harder than winning
the lottery, isn't it?

537
00:40:45,589 --> 00:40:46,632
I'm sorry.

538
00:40:55,432 --> 00:40:56,809
I'm sorry.

539
00:40:58,519 --> 00:40:59,687
I'm sorry.

540
00:41:00,479 --> 00:41:01,522
I'm sorry.

541
00:41:05,484 --> 00:41:06,652
I'm sorry.

542
00:41:10,281 --> 00:41:11,407
I'm sorry.

543
00:41:18,497 --> 00:41:19,748
I'm sorry…

544
00:41:49,653 --> 00:41:52,364
Regarding the pickup
of Keitaro Aikawa's body,

545
00:41:52,448 --> 00:41:55,826
the funeral director should be here
in about 20 minutes.

546
00:41:55,909 --> 00:41:57,786
Okay. Thank you.

547
00:42:06,754 --> 00:42:09,506
Thank you for today.

548
00:42:14,553 --> 00:42:15,387
But,

549
00:42:17,222 --> 00:42:18,807
I think my decision today

550
00:42:20,309 --> 00:42:21,644
was one step away

551
00:42:23,395 --> 00:42:27,316
from rubbing the bereaved mother
the wrong way.

552
00:42:39,662 --> 00:42:40,829
In America,

553
00:42:41,830 --> 00:42:44,875
they call the deceased a "Loved One."

554
00:42:48,128 --> 00:42:49,171
Loved One?

555
00:42:57,054 --> 00:42:58,597
Does that mean someone…

556
00:43:00,599 --> 00:43:02,393
who was important

557
00:43:04,478 --> 00:43:06,146
to someone else?

558
00:43:09,483 --> 00:43:10,818
The term…

559
00:43:13,696 --> 00:43:14,905
is hard to translate.

560
00:43:16,699 --> 00:43:17,700
What?

561
00:43:20,452 --> 00:43:22,579
It's a word only used at the scene,

562
00:43:24,039 --> 00:43:26,625
and also a word only for oneself.

563
00:43:29,002 --> 00:43:31,422
A word only for oneself?

564
00:43:33,257 --> 00:43:34,258
Yes.

565
00:43:37,720 --> 00:43:39,471
Only you can decide

566
00:43:40,639 --> 00:43:43,016
what it means.

567
00:43:45,018 --> 00:43:47,104
Your decision today

568
00:43:47,855 --> 00:43:53,277
was your own way
of facing a Loved One, wasn't it?

569
00:44:36,236 --> 00:44:37,571
The death was caused by a fall.

570
00:44:37,654 --> 00:44:38,864
Is it fun?

571
00:44:38,947 --> 00:44:41,366
Talking about someone's death like that?

572
00:44:41,450 --> 00:44:43,994
<i>If I had known it would be</i>
<i>the last time, I--</i>

573
00:44:44,077 --> 00:44:45,579
It's not over yet.

574
00:44:45,662 --> 00:44:47,122
You're a forensic pathologist.

575
00:44:47,206 --> 00:44:50,042
<i>There may still be a piece</i>
<i>we haven't found yet.</i>

576
00:44:50,125 --> 00:44:51,001
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.

